PreReq

  1. I know how to code in Java.

  2. I know I need to think before I start coding.

  3. I know basic OO concepts (inheritance, polyporphism, …​).

  4. I have understood what a pattern is and I am hungry to learn more than Strategy and Singleton

ObjTD

Study the Factory pattern.

Duration

1 TD and 2 TPs

1. Classroom materials

Do not hesitate to (re)read regularly the Course Material. NOTE: This TD exercise is inspired by the Chapter 4 of the excellent book "Head First: Design Pattern". Bert Bates, Eric Freeman, Elisabeth Freeman, Kathy Sierra. Editions O’Reilly. 2005.

2. O’Reilly pizzeria

You are hired in a pizzeria to do …​ computer science! Last year’s intern who worked on the code left. You only have at your disposal:

  1. The following starting code:

    Code de Pizzeria.java
    /**
 * @author bruel (from O'Reilly Head-First series)
 */
public class Pizzeria {

	public Pizza commanderPizza(String type) {

		Pizza pizza;

		if (type.equals("fromage")) {
			pizza = new PizzaFromage();
		} else if (type.equals("grecque")) {
			pizza = new PizzaGrecque();
		} else {
			pizza = new PizzaPoivrons();
		}

		pizza.preparer();
		pizza.cuire();
		pizza.couper();
		pizza.emballer();

		return pizza;
		}
}

  2. An excerpt of class diagram:

  3. The following testing code:

    Pizzeria boutiqueBrest = new Pizzeria();
boutiqueBrest.commanderPizza("fromage");
...
Pizzeria boutiqueStrasbourg = new Pizzeria();
boutiqueStrasbourg.commanderPizza("grecque");
QUESTION

  1. Identify what varies in that code (if market pressure does add pizza to the menu or if a pizza is no longer successful and needs to disappear, etc.).

  2. Isolate this code in a SimpleFabriqueDePizzas class.

  3. Make the corresponding class diagram.

  4. What is the advantage of doing this? Don’t we transfer just the problem to another object?
You have inherited from this horrible "if then else". In your implementation you might want to use a "switch case" et may be an enum.

3. Almost there…​

We have end up with a clean code that is almost a pattern. Often called Simple Factory, it is nevertheless not considered as a Design Pattern.

3.1. Success of the O’Reilly pizzerias: Franchising the pizza stores

Several cities want to open pizzerias like yours. Your boss, very happy with your programs wants to impose on all future pizzerias to use your codes.

The problem: Strasbourg cheese pizzas are different pizzas with Corsican cheeses!

QUESTION

Propose a solution where SimpleFabriqueDePizzas would be an abstract class.

3.2. Problem: everyone works as they see fit!

Pizzerias use your factories well but have changed their procedures: some do not cut the pizzas, change the cooking times, and O’Reilly pizzerias lose their identity. So we need to restructure the pizzerias.

A highly paid Italian consultant (fortunately in pizzas!) proposes to return to the following structure:

public abstract class Pizzeria {
	public final Pizza commanderPizza(String type) {
		Pizza pizza;

		pizza = creerPizza(type);
		pizza.preparer();
		pizza.cuire();
		pizza.couper();
		pizza.emballer();

		return pizza;
	}

	....... Pizza creerPizza(String type);
}
QUESTION

What are the differences with our current design?

3.3. Allowing the subclasses to decide

3.4. Declaring a factory method

Just by bringing one or two transformations to Pizzeria, we have gone from an object managing the instantiation of our concrete classes to a set of subclasses that now assume this responsibility.

QUESTION

What is the exact declaration of the creerPizza() method of the Pizzeria class ?

3.5. So, how does it work ?

QUESTION

Give a sequence diagram of a "order a cheese pizza of Strasbourg type".
You will implement the missing class in TP.

4. The Factory pattern

Here we are, we have in fact used the Factory pattern

Design pattern : Factory (simple)

Factory defines an interface for creating an objet, but leaving to its subclasses the choice of the class to be instanciated (see also Abstract Factory).

Figure 1. UML model of the Factory pattern
Figure 2. Several examples of Factory pattern definitions

Still hungry?

What about pizzas !?

QUESTION

Write a class diagram for the pizzas (class, attributes & methods).

What would it look like without the pattern ?

A 2013 intern (Design Patterns were not yet in the curriculum) has written the following code:

public class PizzeriaDependante {
	public Pizza creerPizza(String style, String type) {
		Pizza pizza = null;

		if (style.equals("Brest")) {
			if (type.equals("fromage")) {
				pizza = new PizzaFromageStyleBrest();
			} else if (type.equals("vegetarienne")) {
				pizza = new PizzaVegetarienneStyleBrest();
			} else if (type.equals("fruitsDeMer")) {
				pizza = new PizzaFruitsDeMerStyleBrest();
			} else if (type.equals("poivrons")) {
				pizza = new PizzaPoivronsStyleBrest();
			}
		} else if (style.equals("Strasbourg")) {
			if (type.equals("fromage")) {
				pizza = new PizzaFromageStyleStrasbourg();
			} else if (type.equals("vegetarienne")) {
				pizza = new PizzaVegetarienneStyleStrasbourg();
			} else if (type.equals("fruitsDeMer")) {
				pizza = new PizzaFruitsDeMerStyleStrasbourg();
			} else if (type.equals("poivrons")) {
				pizza = new PizzaPoivronsStyleStrasbourg();
			}
		} else {
			System.out.println("Erreur : type de pizza invalide");
			return null;
		}
		pizza.preparer(); pizza.cuire(); pizza.couper(); pizza.emballer();
		return pizza;
	}
}
QUESTION

  1. Count the number of concrete classes on which this class depends.

  2. And what if you add Marseille style pizzas to this Pizzeria?

Back to the adventure game

You surely remind the adventure game application where some of the code resembles this:

Adaptation of behavior to the situation
if (choix.equals("Epee")) {
	perso.setArme(new ComportementEpee());
}
else if (choix.equals("Arc")) {
	perso.setArme(new ComportementArc());
	else if ...
	...
}

This code is not very adaptive and will suffer from changes, for example:

  • change the list of possible weapons

  • add if then else to each new weapon

  • removal of certain weapons

  • …​

QUESTION

  1. Isolate this code in a class SimpleFabriqueArme which will have a method createAreaWeapon (String type) which returns the behavior adapted according to the parameter received.

  2. Give the UML class diagram of the new organization.

  3. What are the differences with the Fabrique pattern? Give some examples of an extension of the adventure game that would correspond to the use of a Factory.

  4. Give the corresponding sequence diagram. For example with the following test code:

    Chevalier perso = new Chevalier("JMI");

SimpleFabriqueArme fabrique = new SimpleFabriqueArme();
ComportementArme c = fabrique.creerComportementArme("Epee");

perso.setArme(c);
perso.frapper();
